  <a href="#1" id="1">
   EARTHQUAKE AFFECTS SAN FRANCISCO, BAY AREA AND CHARLESTON
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Although they are a continent apart, the cities of Charleston, S.C., and San Francisco now share a fateful page in the ledger of time.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   They are the scenes of two of the century's costliest, back-to-back natural disasters: Hurricane Hugo and the Bay Area earthquake. Private groups and officials from Tokyo to London to Charleston, S.C., offered help to the ruptured San Francisco Bay area, but some said relief for the earthquake could drain coffers already strained by previous disasters.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   A major earthquake rocked northern California on Oct. 16, 1989 evening, collapsing part of the San Francisco Bay Bridge and shaking Candlestick Park and buildings up to 95 miles away.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times stronger than one of 6.5. Allen noted that the 1988 report, titled "Probabilities of Large Earthquakes Occurring in California on the San Andreas Fault," presented information that was already widely known among scientists.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   Ever since the 1906 earthquake devastated San Francisco, many scientists have believed the next "big one" would strike the Los Angeles end of the mighty San Andreas Fault .
